Distress Survival Guide Intro
fields.description: Hello, I'm really glad you're here. I want you to know the fact that you picked up this app is a really big deal. You are important and your life is worth saving. After multiple suicide attempts myself and being in and out of hospitals for years, I can say I've been in really dark places myself. When I'm struggling, it's like I have some kind of blinders on where the only way I can see to get me out of my pain is dying. I also want you to know, there is hope, even if you don't believe it. My life is good today, it's good because I put off dying and I learned to ask for help, and use skills to get better. This app will walk you through some activities to help right now, it will guide you through your stability plan and offer you tools and support that you can practice today and anytime you start to feel the need for help. Please hang in there and give this a try. I really want you to stay in this world long enough to get through how you're feeling and realize just how much you matter.

fields.name: Reasons for Living - Walkthrough
fields.description: Reasons for living are the most important things in your life that make you want to keep going even during the hardest moments: your family, pets, seeing tulips bloom, or the remake of your favorite film. For some, they're easy to find. For others, finding even one can feel impossible and may require help and support to find one. When we do identify something, even if it seems small, it can help us get through the darkest of times as help to start building a life we want to live. Once you've identified your reasons for living, the key is to keep them near and in your mind during the difficult moments.

fields.name: Making Home Safer - Walkthrough
fields.description: In moments of extreme distress, it's hard to think clearly. Emotions take over and the urge to die feels like the only way out. We know from people who have survived these feelings that the dark moments pass with time. The idea is that you find ways to get out the darkness and despair while also keeping yourself safe. This starts by giving yourself distance between you and the things you might use to harm or kill yourself. Having a plan is important. It might just be temporary, or one you use permanently. You get to decide. What matters is that you have a plan for yourself so if you find yourself wanting to die again, you are safe and have a chance to (re)build your life that you want to live. Making your home safe may be the single most important thing you can do to save your life.

fields.name: Warning Signals - Stability Plan
fields.description: It's always good to know when you're heading toward the eye of the emotional storm. At a minimum, you can prepare so when it happens, the impact isn't quite so severe. Even better is if you can see the storm coming and start heading in another direction to avoid the crisis altogether. One of the best ways to prepare is to know your own personal warning signals - those things that tell you a crisis is around the corner like certain events, body sensations and the things you do when you're not doing well. The whole idea is to recognize early on when you are going off course and to have a plan when it happens, so you keep working to (re)build the life you want for yourself.

fields.name: Making Home Safer - Stability Plan
fields.description: Overwhelming feelings can make it very hard to think clearly. When this happens, the urge to die can feel like the only way to escape the pain. The fact is that overwhelming emotions do pass with time. One important step you can take for your own safety is to get some distance between you and the things you might use to harm yourself. This can give you enough time for your emotions to pass and for you to take steps to get help. The plan doesn't have to be forever, but long enough to give you a chance to get through dark moments when they come up.. Making your home safe may be the single most important thing you can do to save your life.

fields.name: Reasons for Living - Stability Plan
fields.description: Finding the most important things in your life that makes you want to keep going, even in your darkest moments, can make the difference between life and death. Reasons for Living can be things like your family, friends, pets, spirituality or even just wanting to see spring flowers bloom. For some people, they're easy to find. For others, finding even one can feel impossible and may require help and support to find one. When you do find something, even if it seems small, it can be the seed that will get you through the moment and help you grow a life that you want to live.

fields.name: Coping Strategies - Stability Plan
fields.description: There is no better time to have distress survival skills at the ready than when you're overwhelmed. There are lots of different ways to get through tough times - skills to help you distract so you can take your mind off of your problems for a period of time; to help you feel more comfortable and relaxed in the moment; help you see more clearly; and help you get through intense negative emotions.The idea is to explore different ways to get through really difficult moments. Learn from people with lived experience about coping strategies they found most useful and how they used them.

fields.name: Supportive People - Main video
fields.description: Calling a supportive person might seem easy until you're actually in a crisis. You might start thinking all kinds of reasons why you might not want to reach out for help: Maybe they are busy and you don't want to bother them; your problems aren't big or important enough, or are too big; they have their own problems that are bigger than yours. The list goes on and on. It helps to remember that you chose them for a reason - probably because you know they care about you, want you to stay in the world, and can be helpful. For many people, helping people during their time of need is an honor and a gift; they too feel better having helped. You can just say you want to chat; if you're in trouble, you can get super honest and say you need help and support. The important part is to reach out and not suffer alone.

fields.name: National Hotline - What to Expect
fields.description: After introducing themselves, the first thing the crisis line volunteer may ask you is your name. You don't have to give it if you don't want to. Next, they will ask something like, "What's going on for you today?" At this point, you control the conversation, including what to say and how much detail to provide. Their job then is to listen and offer support. If you are in crisis, they will ask if you have a safety plan for what to do in situations like the one you are in. If you do, they'll help you figure out how best to use it. When callers don't have a safety plan, they will help create one. Their goal in these situations is to think with you about how to stay safe for the next couple of hours and days, and to figure out when it's a good idea to call the crisis line back.

fields.name: Physical Coping Skill
fields.why_text: Intense negative emotions can have a big impact on how we feel physically: our muscles tighten, our hearts race, and we might even feel sick to our stomach. These skills help change how you are feeling emotionally and physically. For example, using an exercise like Paced Breathing helps calm your mind and body so you can relax, feel calmer and more at ease.

fields.name: Coping Distract
fields.why_text: Managing intense negative emotions in the moment can be exhausting and really hard. Distraction is a powerful way to give yourself a break from your problems. They won't help you solve your problems, but they can help to take your mind off of them for a bit, giving you a chance to practice other skills.

fields.name: Coping Help Others
fields.why_text: Helping others when you're in a crisis can have a powerful effect on reducing your own distress. By focusing on others, your mind gets to take a break from your own problems. Studies show that helping others actually changes how people process emotions, helping them to feel happy and content.

fields.name: Coping Courage
fields.why_text: Making changes to improve our lives and move through our problems often takes a lot of courage. It helps to act opposite to how we feel in the moment. For example; If you want to run and hide, you would take a deep breath and take a step forward. If you feel small and powerless, you would can put your shoulders back, raise your head and look forward. The smallest acts of courage can have a powerful impact on how we feel in and about the moment.

fields.name: Coping Senses
fields.why_text: We can't always get away from the situation that is causing us distress as much as we might like to. We can, however, soothe our five senses (touch, smell, sight, hearing, and taste) to make the situation a little easier to stand. For eaxample; you can wear your comfy clothes, light a candle, watch a fire or listen to comforting music.

fields.title: I just want to chat
fields.content: People call the crisis line for all kinds of reasons, including to chat. A common myth is that people only call crises lines when they are completely overwhelmed and in crisis. While it's true that people do call crisis lines when in crises, it's definitely not the only time. You might, for example, have a sense that something is up and you need to talk it through. It could be that you've encountered a warning signal and you know yourself well enough to know that if you don't talk it through, the problem may get more challenging to handle.

fields.title: Don't want police called
fields.content: In the vast majority of cases, the police are not called. In cases where a person is actively suicidal and threatening imminent harm to themselves, the crisis counselor will work with that caller to review all options and, if a call to the police is necessary, ideally make that decision together. While no one likes that scenario, it truly is the best, lifesaving thing a crisis counselor can do in a small number of cases. The goal of a suicide crisis line is to genuinely help you with your personal crisis, not to take away your rights or cause you harm.

fields.title: Thoughts too intense
fields.content: Sometimes people don't call the crisis line because their thoughts or emotions feel too out of control. They fear that the person on the phone won't be able to handle their overwhelming emotions or that the intensity of how they feel will get in the way of being able to talk: What if I start yelling or crying so much it's hard to speak, or I can't find my words? Most crisis line workers have a lot of experience talking to people who are experiencing intense emotions. They can stay on the line with you as long as it takes for you work through your emotions so you can communicate what matters most to you and get the support you need.

fields.title: Don't trust professionals
fields.content: Crisis lines are often staffed by a range of people, including peers (people who have had their own struggles) who are now in a place in their life to help other people and other volunteers. You can always request to speak to a peer or an unpaid volunteer who is not a therapist. You can always end the call if you don't connect or ask for a different person It is more than okay to advocate for yourself to get to the right person.

fields.title: Can't talk on the phone
fields.content: You are in good company. For exactly that reason, it's now possible to text most crisis lines.
Do you have space to listen to what's going on for me? You don't need to solve anything. Just listening would be super helpful.
How is your week going? What's new?
I am going through a lot right now. Do you have a few moments?
I'm having a challenging day, and I was wondering if you could spend some time on the phone with me.
You know how you and I talked about me calling you when I am struggling? I am definitely having that day. Do you have a few minutes?
Hey there. It's me (your name). Do you have a few minutes to chat or are you in the midst of something else?
Thank you so much for talking with me. I really appreciate it.
